            <p><related-object link-type="booklink" source-id="gene" document-id="hlh" document-type="chapter"><bold>Hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis</bold></related-object>
<bold>(HLH)</bold> poses a significant risk for mortality to males with XLP2: 33% of the originally described XLP2 cohort died from HLH between ages six months and 40 years [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="x-lpd.REF.rigaud.2006.110">Rigaud et al 2006</xref>]. Recurrences of HLH are common, particularly within a year of onset of the initial HLH episode [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="x-lpd.REF.pachlopnik_schmid.2011.1522">Pachlopnik Schmid et al 2011</xref>].</p>
            <p><bold>Colitis,</bold> a serious complication of XLP2, has a mortality rate of 60% in symptomatic individuals [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="x-lpd.REF.pachlopnik_schmid.2011.1522">Pachlopnik Schmid et al 2011</xref>].</p>
            <p><bold>Dysgammaglobulinemia.</bold> Approximately one third of males with XLP2 have hypogammaglobulinemia of one or more immunoglobulin subclasses which, if untreated, may result in life-threatening infections. The prognosis for males with this phenotype is more favorable if they are managed with regular IVIG (see Management, <xref ref-type="sec" rid="x-lpd.Treatment_of_Manifestations">Treatment of Manifestations</xref>).</p>
            <p>Transient hypogammaglobulinemia has been reported in a minority of affected males.</p>
            <p>In addition, hypergammaglobulinemia has been reported in two males with XIAP deficiency [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="x-lpd.REF.pachlopnik_schmid.2011.1522">Pachlopnik Schmid et al 2011</xref>].</p>
          </sec>
